# examples/rocky-pxe-lab/hand-walk/Containerfile — reproduce the CIQ article's
# environment so you can walk "Booting Rocky Linux via PXE (Lorax, dnsmasq, TFTP)"
# BY HAND, step-by-step.
#
#   Upstream post : ../upstream-tutorial/  (byte-exact archive + provenance)
#   Canonical URL : https://kb.ciq.com/article/rocky-linux/rl-booting-rocky-linux-via-pxe
#   What it shows : use **Lorax** to build PXE boot images from a Rocky repo, then
#                   serve them with **dnsmasq** (DHCP+TFTP) + HTTP so a machine
#                   network-boots the installer.
#
# This is the HAND-WALK sandbox (TODO #3): a **RHEL-family** box (Lorax + dnsmasq
# + tftp-server are dnf packages) for running the CIQ server stack by hand. The
# INSTALL TARGET is the repo's existing QEMU client (../rocky-pxe-lab.toml).
#
# ── One step is author-only here ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# `lorax` builds boot images via a throwaway install root that needs **loop
# devices + mknod** — which this build sandbox blocks even with --privileged. So
# the Lorax step (RUNBOOK §1) is "run it on your own host"; everything after
# (dnsmasq/TFTP/HTTP) runs here. On your host:
#   phase4-podman/lab-podman.sh build --tag rockypxe-handwalk \
#       --context examples/rocky-pxe-lab/hand-walk
#   podman run --rm -it --privileged -v "$PWD/out:/out:Z" rockypxe-handwalk bash
# (--privileged because Lorax needs real loop/mknod; a normal host grants them.)

# ── Base — Rocky Linux (you're PXE-installing Rocky; Lorax is RHEL-family).
ARG BASE=rockylinux:9
FROM ${BASE}

# ── The article's prerequisites (dnf):
#   lorax        → build the PXE boot images (vmlinuz/initrd/install tree)
#   dnsmasq      → DHCP + TFTP responder (the article's serving core)
#   tftp-server  → the TFTP root layout dnsmasq hands out
#   python3      → simple HTTP server for the install tree + kickstart (:8181)
#   which findutils → the article's shell steps assume them present
RUN dnf install -y --setopt=install_weak_deps=False \
        lorax dnsmasq tftp-server python3 which findutils \
 && dnf clean all

WORKDIR /work
CMD ["bash"]
